I was married 25 years ago today!

I’ve fallen in love with many women over these past 25 years: 

Natalie, the wave loving, Joni Mitchell listening, young convert from California, who introduced me to the Avocado and taught me how to be cool.

Natalie, my young love who let me put flowers in her hair and said “yes” to a life where our dreams for happiness would be intertwined. 

Natalie, the mother overwhelmed by her own love, whose heart expanded to the point of breaking for each child, and whose love became home for us all. 

Natalie, the survivor, who faced inner dragons and balrogs and walked through fire to give herself to me.

Natalie, the wise healer of everyone she comes in contact with. 

Natalie, my support, my counselor, my help mate, my lighthouse, my friend, my Isha. (אִשָּׁה. Woman. - Genesis 2:23). 

I share Adam’s joy at seeing the first woman in an empty world: “This one, at last, is flesh of my flesh and bone of my bone.” 

I have known and fallen in love with so many women over the past 25 years. 

I look forward to the Natalie’s I have yet to meet, and above all, to Natalie in glory.

From the Stefanick family and all of us at Real Life Catholic, Merry Christmas!

social_posts.post_text: Happy new year everyone! 🎉 I hope you realize that change is possible this year. Not because you made a resolution or a goal but because you’re made in God’s image and he has given you volitional will. Make a decision today. Don’t be afraid of commitment. Through prayer and reliance upon Jesus, use your free will to take small daily steps to becoming who God created you to be. With God all things are possible! Renounce the lies of the evil one and start today. How are you being called to change in this season of your life?

I hung out with my good friend, Jeremy Rivera @jeremydreams , recently and listen to what he has to say about what it’s all about. Did you know that sharing our faith with others (evangelization) is the “deepest identity” of the Church. In fact, Pope Paul VI made it very clear, in his encyclical Evangelii Nuntiandi, that the Church “exists in order to evangelize.” It’s the very reason Christ has not come back, he wants more souls at the great banquet. Let’s keep the party in heaven going by bringing more souls with us!

We all know the Bible says to “love your neighbor as yourself.” But here’s the funny thing: We’re usually better at loving our neighbor than loving ourselves!
 
Sure, we all get a little down on ourselves sometimes. But God doesn’t want you to constantly focus on what’s wrong with yourself. He wants you to love yourself – and He’s better at affirmation than anyone else! And this is so vital to remember that we wanted to reshare this incredible episode with you again.
 
So, if you want the joy that comes from replacing your negative self-talk with God’s Word, then this latest episode on the Chris Stefanick Show may be the most important thing you watch all week! 
￼

As we reflect on St. Valentine’s Day, it is a great opportunity to reflect on the true meaning of love in our lives. While this holiday is often associated with romantic love, it is important to remember that love takes many different forms. This video tells the story of a very vulnerable time in Natalie and I’s marriage. I share this story now in the hope of encouraging others who may be discouraged or want to flee the reality of their lives.

In the Catholic faith, love is viewed as a self-giving, sacrificial act that is rooted in the love of God. This kind of love is not just a feeling or an emotion, but a choice that we make to put the needs of others before our own.
My advice: get married and have kids as fast as you can so that you can get to the grandkids.

“In good times and in bad” (or some variant) is a vital part of the marriage vows every Catholic couple says on their wedding day.

But sometimes those “bad times” are actually much worse than we expect. Coldness, selfishness, infidelity, and more can make many couples’ marriages go from a fairy tale to a nightmare, and healing the resulting wounds can feel impossible.

Fortunately, there is a way to find love, tenderness, and forgiveness in your marriage. Our guests, Jackie and Wadi Barreto, work for Retrouvaille, a marriage healing organization that has rescued thousands of couples from divorce and marital strife.

You’ll hear about their experience in helping countless couples reconcile, and learn how to strengthen your own marriage BEFORE it encounters these kinds of struggles.

If you’ve ever gone through “bad times” in your marriage, you’ll definitely want to see this! @formedcatholic

Have you ever noticed how God changes people’s names throughout the Bible? Jacob wrestles the angel and becomes Israel, Simon the fisherman is later called Peter, and the once legalistic persecutor of the Church, Saul, becomes the great Apostle Paul. These are just a few examples. But why the changing of their names?

It’s because our name is central to our identity. Almighty God knows that once we encounter him, we often have a lot of baggage to let go of in order to become who he’s calling us to be and do what he’s calling us to do. God knows our potential. He sees and believes the best out of us, often much more than we believe about ourselves. This truth about our identity is so powerful, it’s been said that God knows our sins but calls us by our true name; the Devil knows our true name but calls us by our sins.

So who are you at your core? What defines you at your deepest level of being? God wants you to know in your mind and in our heart that you are his beloved son or daughter. The reason this truth is so critically important is because remembering who we are (and whose we are) will greatly impact how think about ourselves, which impacts how we feel, and ultimately, how we live and act in our daily lives.

My prayer for you this week is that you will take a few moments to reflect again on how much you mean to God and listen to the ‘still small voice’ that calls you his beloved. The fact that he bankrupted heaven to redeem you with the blood of his only begotten Son proves that your life is not defined by the sum of your pluses or minuses, nor by your virtues or vices, but by the sum of the Father’s love for you. Let that sink in the rest of this week!

These are gifts from God that will bring life to your spirit and help renew your joy for the road of faith ahead.
